NOTES_2TIMOTHY = {
    1: {
        1: 'GREEK: "Apostolos" (ἀπόστολος, Strong\'s G652) denotes one sent with full authority, a commissioned envoy. "Kat\' epangelian zōēs" (according to the promise of life) indicates that Paul\'s apostleship is oriented toward the promise of life found in Christ Jesus—the genitive "tēs en Christō Iēsou" qualifies this life as exclusively located in the Anointed One.',
        2: 'THEOLOGICAL: The triad "grace, mercy, peace" (charis, eleos, eirēnē) is unique to the Pastoral Epistles among Pauline salutations—most others omit "mercy" (eleos). The coordination of "God the Father and Christ Jesus our Lord" as a single source of divine blessing reflects the highest Christological claim, placing the Son alongside the Father as co-bestower of covenant blessings (cf. Titus 1:4).',
        6: 'GREEK: "Anazōpyrein" (ἀναζωπυρεῖν, Strong\'s G329) is a NT hapax legomenon meaning literally "to rekindle" or "to fan back into full flame." The prefix ana- (again) with zōpyron (live coal) creates a vivid metaphor of spiritual gift as smoldering fire requiring intentional tending. "Charisma" (χάρισμα, G5486) here denotes a divinely bestowed empowerment received through apostolic ordination.',
        7: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Pneuma deilias" (spirit of cowardice) stands in contrast to a threefold positive endowment: dynamis (power), agapē (love), and sōphronismos (sound-mindedness). "Sōphronismos" (σωφρονισμός, G4995) is another NT hapax legomenon, denoting self-disciplined clarity of mind. This verse grounds Christian boldness not in human resolve but in the very nature of the Spirit given by God.',
        9: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Pro chronōn aiōniōn" (before eternal ages) places God\'s salvific purpose and grace in a pretemporal decree—grace was given "in Christ Jesus" before time itself began. This echoes the divine council\'s eternal purpose (Eph 1:4, 3:11). TYPOLOGY: The language of holy calling (klēsis hagia) recalls Israel\'s election (Deut 7:6) now extended through Christ to all who believe—not by works but by divine purpose and grace.',
        10: 'GREEK: "Epiphaneia" (ἐπιφάνεια, G2015) carries strong connotations of a divine manifestation or royal appearing, used in Hellenistic contexts for the visible arrival of a god or emperor. Paul applies it to the incarnation of Jesus Christ. THEOLOGICAL: Christ\'s abolition (katargēsantos) of death and illumination (phōtisantos) of life and incorruptibility (aphtharsian) through the gospel constitutes the decisive reversal of the Adamic curse (Rom 5:12-21; 1 Cor 15:26).',
        12: 'GREEK: "Parathēkē" (παραθήκη, G3866) is a legal-financial term meaning "deposit" or "that which is entrusted"—here it refers to either the gospel entrusted to God for safekeeping, or Paul\'s own life entrusted to Christ. THEOLOGICAL: Paul\'s confidence rests not in his own faithfulness but in Christ\'s ability (dynatos estin) to guard the deposit "unto that day" (eis ekeinēn tēn hēmeran), a reference to the eschatological Day of the Lord (cf. 2 Tim 4:8).',
        14: 'THEOLOGICAL: The "good deposit" (kalēn parathēkēn) shifts from v.12—there Paul entrusts his deposit to God; here Timothy is charged to guard the apostolic deposit of sound teaching. The agent of this guarding is the Holy Spirit indwelling the community ("in us," en hēmin), indicating that doctrinal faithfulness is a pneumatological work, not merely human effort. DIVINE_COUNCIL: The Spirit\'s indwelling presence echoes the OT temple theology where God\'s Spirit dwelt among his people (Ezek 36:27; 37:14).',
        18: 'GREEK: The double use of "kyrios" (Lord) in "may the Lord grant him to find mercy from the Lord" is striking. Many scholars note that the first "kyrios" likely refers to Christ (to whom Paul prays) and the second to God the Father as eschatological judge, though the interchangeability itself reflects the high Christology of the Pastorals. HISTORICAL: Onesiphorus\'s search for Paul in Rome suggests Paul was not easily found, consistent with a second Roman imprisonment under harsher conditions than Acts 28.',
    },
    2: {
        1: 'GREEK: "Be strengthened" (ἐνδυναμοῦ, endynamoō, Strong\'s G1743) is a present passive imperative — Timothy is commanded to continually receive empowerment, not generate it himself. The passive voice indicates the source of strength is the grace of Christ, not human effort. THEOLOGICAL: This sets the tone for the entire chapter: faithful endurance is grounded in divine grace mediated through union with Christ Jesus.',
        2: 'THEOLOGICAL: This verse establishes a four-generation chain of apostolic transmission: Paul → Timothy → faithful men → others. The term παράθου (parathou, "entrust," aorist middle imperative of παρατίθημι, G3908) is a banking term meaning to deposit something valuable for safekeeping. HISTORICAL: "Through many witnesses" (διὰ πολλῶν μαρτύρων) likely refers to the public context of Timothy\'s ordination or Paul\'s public teaching, not private instruction alone.',
        3: 'GREEK: συγκακοπάθησον (synkakopathēson, G4777) is a compound verb: σύν (together) + κακοπαθέω (to suffer evil). This rare word emphasizes shared suffering with Paul and with Christ. The military metaphor "good soldier of Christ Jesus" (καλὸς στρατιώτης) initiates the first of three vocational analogies (soldier, athlete, farmer) in vv. 3-6.',
        8: 'THEOLOGICAL: This is a creedal summary: "raised from the dead" affirms bodily resurrection; "of the seed of David" affirms Messianic lineage and fulfillment of the Davidic covenant (2 Sam 7:12-16). TYPOLOGY: The dual emphasis on Davidic descent and resurrection echoes Romans 1:3-4, linking Jesus\' human kingship with his divine vindication. The perfect passive participle ἐγηγερμένον (egēgermenon) denotes a completed action with abiding results — Christ remains in the state of having been raised.',
        11: 'STRUCTURE: Verses 11-13 form a "faithful saying" (πιστὸς ὁ λόγος), likely an early Christian hymn or confessional formula. The four conditional (εἰ) statements create a chiastic pattern: two positive promises (co-dying/co-living, enduring/co-reigning) and two sobering warnings (denying/being denied, faithlessness/God\'s faithfulness). TYPOLOGY: "Died together with" (συναπεθάνομεν) echoes baptismal theology of Romans 6:8, linking sacramental death with eschatological life.',
        13: 'THEOLOGICAL: This is among the most profound statements of divine faithfulness in Scripture. God\'s fidelity is not contingent upon human fidelity but grounded in his own immutable nature. "To deny himself he is not able" (ἀρνήσασθαι ἑαυτὸν οὐ δύναται) — God\'s covenant faithfulness flows from his very being; unfaithfulness would be self-contradiction. This does not negate v. 12\'s warning but grounds God\'s judgment and mercy alike in his unchanging character.',
        15: 'GREEK: ὀρθοτομοῦντα (orthotomounta, G3718) literally means "cutting straight" — a hapax legomenon in the NT, possibly drawn from tent-making (cutting fabric straight), road-building, or stone-masonry. It denotes precision and integrity in handling the word of truth. THEOLOGICAL: The triad "approved" (δόκιμον, tested as genuine), "unashamed" (ἀνεπαίσχυντον), and "rightly dividing" establishes the standard for ministerial faithfulness.',
        19: 'TYPOLOGY: The two seal inscriptions echo Numbers 16:5 LXX ("The Lord knew those who are his") from the Korah rebellion, and likely Isaiah 26:13 or Numbers 16:26. The pairing links divine election with the ethical demand for holiness. DIVINE_COUNCIL: God\'s sovereign knowledge of his own people (Ἔγνω κύριος τοὺς ὄντας αὐτοῦ) reflects the divine prerogative of intimate, covenantal knowing — not mere cognition but ownership and election. THEOLOGICAL: The "firm foundation" (στερεὸς θεμέλιος) stands in contrast to the crumbling faith of those deceived by Hymenaeus and Philetus.',
        21: 'GREEK: δεσπότης (despotēs, G1203) is used here rather than κύριος — it denotes an absolute master or owner of a household, emphasizing sovereign authority over the vessels. THEOLOGICAL: Human moral agency ("if anyone cleanses himself") and divine purpose ("sanctified," "prepared" — both passive participles) are held in tension: the vessel acts, yet its sanctified and prepared state is divinely wrought.',
        25: 'GREEK: μετάνοιαν (metanoian, G3341) — repentance — is here described as something God "may give" (δώῃ, subjunctive of δίδωμι), indicating repentance is ultimately a divine gift, not merely a human decision. THEOLOGICAL: The subjunctive μήποτε δώῃ ("if perhaps God may give") preserves genuine uncertainty about the outcome while affirming God\'s sovereignty over the process of conversion. This balances human responsibility (v. 21, self-cleansing) with divine initiative.',
        26: 'GREEK: ἀνανήψωσιν (ananēpsōsin, G366) means literally "to return to soberness" — the image is of awakening from a drunken stupor. DIVINE_COUNCIL: The "snare of the devil" (τοῦ διαβόλου παγίδος) reflects the adversarial role of the diábolos as a cosmic agent who entraps humans. The verb ἐζωγρημένοι (ezōgrēmenoi, G2221, "taken alive/captured") is a military term — the same word Luke 5:10 uses for "catching" men, creating a stark contrast between being captured by the devil and being captured for life by God.',
    },
    3: {
        1: 'GREEK: "Perilous" (χαλεποί, chalepoi, Strong\'s G5467) occurs only here and in Matt 8:28 (describing the Gadarene demoniacs as "fierce"). It denotes something difficult, dangerous, or hard to bear. "Last days" (ἐσχάταις ἡμέραις) is a technical eschatological phrase indicating the messianic age inaugurated by Christ\'s first coming and extending to His return (cf. Acts 2:17; Heb 1:2). THEOLOGICAL: Paul views the present church age as already participating in the "last days," not merely a future period.',
        3: 'GREEK: "Without natural affection" (ἄστοργοι, astorgoi, G794) denotes absence of familial love (storgē), particularly between parents and children. "Slanderers" (διάβολοι, diaboloi) is the same word used as a title for the devil (G1228), literally "one who throws accusations across" — these persons take on the character of the accuser himself. "Hostile to what is good" (ἀφιλάγαθοι, aphilagathoi, G865) is a NT hapax legomenon, a compound of alpha-privative + philos + agathos.',
        5: 'GREEK: "Form" (μόρφωσιν, morphōsin, G3446) denotes an outward shape or semblance, distinct from μορφή (morphē) which can imply inner reality (cf. Phil 2:6). Paul deliberately chooses the word for external appearance. THEOLOGICAL: This verse describes the essence of apostasy — retaining religious externals while denying the supernatural power (δύναμιν) that animates true godliness. The perfect participle ἠρνημένοι ("having denied") indicates a settled, completed rejection.',
        8: 'HISTORICAL: Jannes and Jambres are not named in the Hebrew Bible but were widely known in Second Temple Jewish tradition as the Egyptian magicians who opposed Moses before Pharaoh (Exod 7:11-12). They appear in the Targum of Pseudo-Jonathan, the Dead Sea Scrolls (CD 5:17-19), and Pliny. TYPOLOGY: As these sorcerers imitated Moses\'s signs with counterfeit power, so false teachers in the last days imitate godliness while opposing truth. "Corrupted in mind" (κατεφθαρμένοι τὸν νοῦν) is a perfect passive participle indicating a thoroughly ruined intellect. "Disqualified" (ἀδόκιμοι, G96) means failing the test, rejected as counterfeit — the same metallurgical metaphor Paul applies to himself in 1 Cor 9:27.',
        12: 'THEOLOGICAL: This is among the New Testament\'s most unqualified statements on suffering. The future passive διωχθήσονται ("shall be persecuted") is not conditional but declarative — persecution is the normative experience for all (πάντες) who resolve (θέλοντες, present active participle indicating ongoing desire) to live godly lives "in Christ Jesus." The prepositional phrase ἐν Χριστῷ Ἰησοῦ locates both the godly life and its resulting persecution within the sphere of union with Christ.',
        15: 'GREEK: "Sacred writings" (ἱερὰ γράμματα, hiera grammata) is a phrase used in Hellenistic Judaism for the Hebrew Scriptures (cf. Josephus, Ant. 10.210). This is distinct from γραφή (graphē) used in v. 16, though both refer to the Old Testament. "From infancy" (ἀπὸ βρέφους) — βρέφος (G1025) denotes a newborn or nursing infant, indicating Timothy\'s exposure to Scripture from the earliest age through his Jewish mother Eunice and grandmother Lois (2 Tim 1:5). THEOLOGICAL: The Scriptures\' purpose is soteriological — "to make wise unto salvation" — but only "through faith that is in Christ Jesus," establishing that the OT rightly read points to and culminates in the Messiah.',
        16: 'GREEK: "God-breathed" (θεόπνευστος, theopneustos, G2315) is a NT hapax legomenon — a compound of θεός (God) and πνέω (to breathe/blow). It does not mean "inspired" in the modern sense of human creativity but rather "expired" — breathed out by God Himself. The word emphasizes divine origin, not human experience. "Reproof" translates ἐλεγμόν (elegmon, G1650), also a NT hapax, denoting conviction of error or refutation. THEOLOGICAL: Paul predicates θεόπνευστος of πᾶσα γραφή ("all/every Scripture"), affirming the divine origin of the entirety of the sacred writings. The four purposes — teaching, reproof, correction, training in righteousness — form a comprehensive scope: establishing truth, exposing error, restoring the fallen, and cultivating ongoing righteousness.',
        17: 'GREEK: "Complete" (ἄρτιος, artios, G739) is a NT hapax legomenon meaning fitted, capable, proficient — describing a state of readiness for one\'s task. "Thoroughly equipped" (ἐξηρτισμένος, exērtismenos, G1822) is a perfect passive participle from ἐξαρτίζω, intensifying the concept with the prefix ἐξ- (out, completely). THEOLOGICAL: The "man of God" (ὁ τοῦ θεοῦ ἄνθρωπος) echoes an OT title for prophets and servants of the Lord (1 Sam 9:6; 1 Kgs 17:18; cf. 1 Tim 6:11), placing Timothy in that prophetic lineage. Scripture\'s sufficiency is the ground of the minister\'s completeness for every good work.',
    },
    4: {
        1: 'GREEK: Diamartýromai (Strong\'s G1263) is an intensified form of martyréō, meaning "to solemnly witness/charge"—carrying a legal, covenantal weight. The phrase "the living and the dead" (zōntas kai nekrous) is a merism encompassing all humanity under Christ\'s judicial authority. THEOLOGICAL: Paul grounds his final charge in the eschatological realities of Christ\'s role as universal Judge and King—his epipháneia (appearing) and basileía (kingdom) forming the twin horizons of apostolic hope (cf. Acts 10:42, 1 Pet 4:5).',
        2: 'GREEK: Kḗryxon (G2784, aorist imperative) means "herald" or "proclaim as a herald"—the word evokes a royal herald announcing a king\'s decree. Ephístēthi (G2186) literally means "stand upon" or "be at hand," conveying urgent readiness. The string of aorist imperatives (élengxon, epitímēson, parakáleson) conveys decisive, immediate action. STRUCTURE: Five sharp imperatives form a staccato rhythm in Greek, reflecting the urgency of the charge.',
        3: 'GREEK: Hygiaínousa didaskalía ("sound doctrine") uses a medical metaphor—hygiaínō (G5198) means "to be healthy/whole." Episōreúousin (G2002) is a vivid hapax-like compound meaning "to heap up upon"—picturing an excessive accumulation of teachers. Knēthómenoi tēn akoḗn ("having the hearing tickled") uses knḗthō, meaning "to scratch/itch," found only here in the NT. THEOLOGICAL: Paul warns of a consumerist approach to teaching where desire rather than truth determines doctrine.',
        6: 'GREEK: Spéndomai (G4689) means "I am being poured out as a libation/drink offering"—a present passive indicating a process already underway. This sacrificial imagery echoes Phil 2:17. Análysis (G359) appears only here in the NT, meaning "a loosing, departure"—used of breaking camp or loosing a ship from moorings. TYPOLOGY: Paul casts his death as a priestly drink offering (cf. Num 15:5-10; Phil 2:17), framing martyrdom as liturgical sacrifice to God.',
        7: 'GREEK: All three verbs are in the perfect tense (ēgṓnismai, tetéleka, tetḗrēka), indicating completed action with enduring results. Agōna (G73) denotes an athletic contest or struggle. Drómos (G1408) is a racecourse (cf. Acts 20:24). STRUCTURE: The triadic structure—fight/course/faith—moves from combat to athletics to stewardship, encompassing the full scope of Paul\'s apostolic life.',
        8: 'GREEK: Stéphanos tēs dikaiosýnēs ("crown of righteousness") uses stéphanos (G4735), the victor\'s wreath, not diádēma (a royal crown). Apókeitai (G606) means "is stored up/reserved"—a banking or treasury term. THEOLOGICAL: The crown is awarded by Christ as díkaios kritḗs ("righteous Judge"), contrasting Roman courts that condemned Paul. This reward extends to all who have agapēkósi ("have loved," perfect active participle) his epipháneia—a present love for a future reality (cf. Rev 22:20).',
        14: 'GREEK: Chalkeús (G5471) means "coppersmith" or "metalworker"—appearing only here in the NT. Endeíknymi (G1731) means "to demonstrate/show forth." HISTORICAL: This Alexander may be the same figure mentioned in 1 Tim 1:20. The phrase "the Lord will render to him according to his works" echoes Ps 62:12 (LXX 61:13) and Prov 24:12, entrusting vengeance to divine justice rather than human retaliation (cf. Rom 12:19).',
        17: 'GREEK: Parástē (G3936, aorist) means "stood beside"—a legal term for an advocate standing with someone in court. Enedynámōsen (G1743) means "empowered from within." TYPOLOGY: "Delivered out of the mouth of the lion" (ek stómatos léontos) echoes Ps 22:21 (LXX 21:22) and Dan 6:22, placing Paul\'s deliverance in the typological pattern of God rescuing the righteous from bestial powers. The lion may symbolize Satan (1 Pet 5:8), Nero, or death itself.',
        18: 'THEOLOGICAL: Paul\'s confidence moves from past deliverance (v.17) to future salvation—not from physical death but "into his heavenly kingdom" (eis tēn basileían autou tēn epouránion). The doxology "unto the ages of the ages" (eis tous aiōnas tōn aiōnōn) is the strongest Greek expression of eternity, directed here to the Lord Jesus, affirming his divine status. This forms an inclusio with v.1, where Christ\'s kingdom and appearing frame the entire chapter.',
        22: 'GREEK: The singular "your spirit" (tou pneúmatós sou) addresses Timothy personally, while "with you" (meth\' hymōn) shifts to the plural, indicating the letter was meant to be read to the wider community. STRUCTURE: This dual benediction—one personal, one communal—forms a fitting close to Paul\'s final letter, balancing intimate pastoral care with ecclesial scope.',
    },
}